node.text: I first endorsed Bernie in 2016. A candidate not beholden to the ruling class. A candidate who was fighting against the effects of marginalization that impacted me (a queer woman, raised poor in an American suburb in a multiracial family) for my entire life. No matter my life and status have changed since then, one thing has always remained the same: There is no amount of money I could ever make or keep that I would EVER choose over the pursuit of more equally distributed resources for ALL. There is no system of benefits that could justify my participation in rigging American institutions for personal gain and wealth consolidation. When I look at some of the other candidates, or members of my newfound class, I see actions that have nothing to do with being wealthy and everything to do with being selfish. That’s why I am officially (re)endorsing Bernie Sanders for president.

node.text:
If I Can’t Have Love, I Want Power

This album is a concept album about the joys and horrors of pregnancy and childbirth. It was very important to me that the cover art conveyed the sentiment of my journey over the past few months. The dichotomy of the Madonna and the Whore. The idea that me as a sexual being and my body as a vessel and gift to my child are two concepts that can co-exist peacefully and powerfully. My body has belonged to the world in many different ways the past few years, and this image is my means of reclaiming my autonomy and establishing my pride and strength as a life force for my human being. 

 
This cover image celebrates pregnant and postpartum bodies as something beautiful, to be admired. We have a long way to go with eradicating the social stigma around bodies & breastfeeding. I hope this can be a step in the right direction!

My fourth album, out August 27, 2021

Cover Photo by @lucasgarrrido

node.text: This week, 155 years after the first Juneteenth celebration, the United States has finally recognized Juneteenth as a federal holiday. It’s a step in the right direction, but it’s also just a bandaid covering up myriad challenges facing Black Americans in 2021. Today, I implore you to educate yourself on Black History, support Black-owned businesses and creatives with your dollars, and donate to organizations still fighting for racial justice in America.
